Very beautiful green space (which dates from 1858) with its 2 symmetrical pools (and their sculptures) and its beautiful trees. Pleasant in hot weather!

Pretty tree-lined square with 2 fountains ‚õ≤Ô∏è, play areas. Designed in the French style, this green space was created by Gabriel Davioud on the occasion of the major urbanization works undertaken by Napoleon III and Baron Haussmann. Formerly Square des Arts et M√©tiers, it now bears the name of a municipal councilor from the 3rd arrondissement in the 19th century. Two groups of bronze sculptures adorn its pools. One represents Agriculture and Industry, the other, Mercury and Music. These works are respectively signed by Charles Gumery (1827-1871) and Auguste-Louis-Marie Ottin (1811-1890). The central column, made of Jura granite, was erected to the glory of Napoleonic victories. The bronze bust, work of Costas Spourdos, represents Marc Seguin (1786-1875), French engineer.
Beautiful shaded square with 2 beautiful fountains which freshen the air. A small play area for children and a beautiful view of the facade of the Conservatory of Arts and Crafts
Very pleasant square when there is sunshine. Very beautiful fountain with lots of benches, where everyone has space to do what they want (reading, games, tanning, sports).

Nice square but not very isolated from the surrounding neighborhood and above all extremely dangerous for small children who can easily open the gates and go into the street (I myself had to catch up with a small child who had left)

This garden is the first square in Paris designed ‚Äúin the French style‚Äù, according to the wishes of Napoleon III. A Saint-Ylie stone balustrade surrounds the square, which reveals regular paths punctuated with staggered horse chestnut trees and a lonely Crimean lime tree. Get closer to the balustrade, you will be able to see numerous fossilized shells and even coral remains in this white limestone rock! There are two basins, each composed of two imposing bronze statues designed by Davioud in 1860: Agriculture and Industry by Gumery (1827-1871) and Mercury and Music by Ottin (1811-1867). The Napoleonic victories of Alma (1854), Inkermann (1854), Tchernaia (1855) and S√©bastopol (1855) stand out on a solemn granite column from the Jura, not far from which you will discover a more modest bronze representing Marc Seguin, by Costa Spourdos (1987). The park is clean and fairly well used during the day.

An impeccable green space. It is a real gem for the residents of the surrounding neighborhoods. In fact, Paris is far from being a green city compared to Berlin, Vienna, etc. According to a census, the number of trees in the City of Lights is only 184,500. Most of them are planted along the streets. Despite this, throughout the Haussmann neighborhoods there is a virtual absence of greenery. ‚ÄúParis is beautiful but monotonous. It noticeably lacks trees,‚Äù my Lithuanian friend commented on his beloved city. And he's not wrong.
